ond to the violence done against them, alternating close readings of writings by James Baldwin, Tennessee Williams, Jean Toomer, Dorothy Allison, and Stephen Crane with critical legal and political analyses of Supreme Court Cases and anti-gay legislation. He also pays deep attention to the political strategies, public declarations, websites, interviews, and other media made by key religious right organizations that have mounted the most successful regulations and condemnations of homosexuality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHate speechxUnited States. 0aHate speechzUnited States. 0aHomosexualityxPolitical aspectsxUnited States. 0aHomosexualityxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aHomosexualityxReligious aspectsxChristianityxUnited States. 0aHomosexualityxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectsxUnited States. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aRhetoricxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Gay Studies.2bisacsh  aAmerican.  aCobb.  aFags.  aHates.  aMichael.  aThough.  aactivism.  aanti-gay.  acentury.  acontemporary.  aculture.  acuriously.  adiscourses.  aexpression.  afigured.  aforms.  agenres.  ahave.  along.  amaintains.  amost.  apervasive.  apolitics.  apotent.  aqueer.  areligious.  athat.  athought.  athroughout.  atwentieth.  avirulently.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081471668740uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814790199.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814790199423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814790199/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013